                    <span>This was the first book I read on wealth.  It is inspiring and you can learn more on each read.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">This was the starting point of the self-improvement industry</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      /
                      <span>5</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-23</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I'm not sure how I was ever so blessed, but Dr. Napoleon Hill worked for me the last two years of his life - or, more accurately - he was "given to me" for that special period of time.
<br />
<br />Here's how it happened:
<br />
<br />My boss at the time, William Penn Patrick, had been named by Dr. Hill as one of the six most important people in the 20th Century. Bill, in turn, paid Dr. Hill some amount of money(?) to be my personal advisor. Thank God!
<br />
<br />Although Dr. Hill was, by that time, physically frail, he was still as mentally sharp as ever. And, as a result, of immeasurable help to me - - who was, at that time, just an immature 28 year-old kid.
<br />
<br />To this day - 40 years after the first time I read it - I still start reading "Think and Grow Rich" on Jaunuary 1st of every year. And, whenever someone asks me how/why I've been so successful in selling/life, Napoleon Hill and his classic book, "Think and Grow Rich," are still among the first reasons I give.
<br />
<br />Even now, after all these years, rarely do I conduct a sales training seminar for "The Closers" series, or do a coaching/ consulting sales training session, without refering to Dr. Hill and what he taught me. Translation: Buy the book! 
<br />
<br />Note: You may have noticed that all of my book reviews carry "5 Star" ratings (*****). But that's not the sign of a "soft reviewer." I only review books to which I can honestly give a "5 Star" rating. You may assume, therefore, that any sales training/self-improvement book without my "5 Star" rating is either something less that "5 Star," or I simply haven't gotten to it yet . . . and there are certainly plenty of those!
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />   </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Super audio!</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
